		<credit project="CfPBoK@https://slebok.github.io/cfpbok/"/>
		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2009"></a><br><code>sle2009/paper01</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2009</a> paper:</span><br><i>Language Evolution in Practice: The History of GMF</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/MarkusHerrmannsdörfer.html">Markus Herrmannsdörfer</a>, <a href="../profile/DanielRatiu.html">Daniel Ratiu</a>, <a href="../profile/GuidoWachsmuth.html">Guido Wachsmuth</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-12107-4_3">10.1007/978-3-642-12107-4_3</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t2b.html"><span class="tagM">T2B: Evolution</span></a><ul><li> The paper is explicitly about how the GMF language/tooling evolved over time and what that evolution looked like in practice.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL">T4A: Workbenches</span></a><ul><li> GMF is a language workbench/tooling platform, so the narrative is grounded in evolution of meta-tools.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t2a.html"><span class="tagL">T2A: Lifecycle</span></a><ul><li> It also concerns lifecycle aspects of a language framework (changes, migration, and long-term sustainability).
</li></ul></li></ul>
